{"questionId":"25417","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>This question asks you to explore properties of a family of curves of the type</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math> <strong>for various values of</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> <strong>and</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>, <strong>where</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℕ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now, consider curves of the form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>≥</mo><mo>-</mo><mroot><mi>b</mi><mn>3</mn></mroot></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Next, consider the curve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence deduce that the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math>has no local minimum or maximum points.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>local minima/maxima occur when<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> has no (real) solutions (or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>⇒</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>so, no local minima/maxima exist&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25417","referenceCode":"22M.3.AHL.TZ2.1d.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence deduce that the curve y2=x3+x has no local minimum or maximum points.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}